TikTok hides objectionable videos from users
According to TikTok’s data, its number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are younger than 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
The Chinese social network TikTok censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong, the Guardian reports.
The documents at the outlet’s disposal reveal that the owner of TikTok (the company ByteDance) is using the app to promote China’s foreign policy goals abroad.
The majority of the violations pertaining to Chinese policy falls under “incitement of hatred.”
In each case, TikTok puts the objectionable publications in a context complying with the general rules, so the social network's actions won’t look like censorship.
For example, the ban on criticizing China’s socialist system falls under the general ban on “criticizing or attacking the policies and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.”.
The ban on mentioning the incident on Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the “falsification of the history of China or other countries.”
The document also provides a list of twenty names of “foreign leaders or state figures” that are banned, including the North Korean leaders Kim Jong-il, Kim Il-sung, Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, American presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hye, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
Banned material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are deleted by the social network’s administrators and may result in the user being blocked.
Less severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their reach is limited by TikTok’s algorithms.
ByteDance representatives told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer used: “We use a localized approach for moderation now, and we engage independent local specialists”.
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says Production Center co-founder Rustem Bogdanov.
Production Center is one Russian media company that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All of Production Center’s bloggers’ advertising materials are coordinated with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be published without coordination, says Bogdanov.
To the question of whether it’s possible to talk about politics or Putin on TikTok, Bogdanov answers positively and says he has seen such posts.
The founder of the Our Digital agency Roman Zaripov agrees with Bogdanov: “The basic rules for TikTok users are enumerated in the user agreement: you cannot post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on.”
But these rules can be applied to any content the moderators don’t like, notes Zaripov.
Zaripov’s agency is another of TikTok’s Russian partners.
According to TikTok’s data, its number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are younger than 18.
According to the user agreement, only people older than 13 can use TikTok.
The social network’s administrators check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: Neuronet analyzes their faces and determines how old the person looks, says Bogdanov.
If Neuronet decides the user is younger, his account could be deleted, he adds.
According to RBK, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow at the WeWork co-working space.
