Russians warned about fake calls from banks
The number of calls from scammers spoofing banks' telephone numbers is increasing in Russia.
This was reported by Kommerstant with reference to information from the Central Bank.
In the summer of 2019, the regulator passed information to communications operators about more than 2.5 thousand numbers that clients of various financial organizations were called from.
In 189 cases, operators discovered a spoofed number.
Another 218 numbers were blocked, and in 59 cases, restrictions were placed on the use of financial services.
The Deputy Head of the Central Bank's Department of Information Safety, Artem Sychev, said that a wide range of Russian banks encountered spoofed numbers.
He explained that operators don't always respond to the Central Bank's warnings about fraudulent calls, citing the lack of such requirement in the law "On Communications".
Otkritie, Rosbank, and Alfa-Bank confirmed the information about the increase in the number of fraudulent calls from spoofed numbers.
According to the Beeline press service, some of the information about fraudulent calls that was passed on by the Central Bank was incorrect: the list included numbers that banks actually use to communicate with clients.
Blocking them would lead to a breakdown in the organizations' work.
Artem Sychev said that the Central Bank plans to create a database of scammer numbers that communications operators will use to check the number of every call.
He explained that legislative amendments are required to create such a database.
