Within 24 hours a petition for Ustinov's release collected more than 112 thousand signatures.
Theater and cinema artists began a flashmob in support of their colleague.
A line to participate in the one-person picket as a sign of solidarity with the actor formed on 18 September on Staraya ploshchad.
Rights advocates, journalists, academics, teachers, doctors and Orthodox clergy demanded a retrial.
Ustinov's sister Yulia told Interfax that her brother does not plan to speak at a rally in the capital on 29 September in support of "Moscow case" defendants.
"Sanctions" shipments to Russia fell to 1% of previous level
The Russian government calculated that shipments of agricultural products and foodstuffs to Russia from countries that fell under the Russian food import ban had fallen since 2013 to less than 1% of their previous level.
According to a report sent to Russian president Vladimir Putin, 31 thousand tons of products were shipped from sanctioned countries in the first half of 2019, compared with 3 million 442.2 thousand tons in the same period of 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time the value of the imported products fell to $226.5 million from $4 billion 975.5 million respectively.
This refers to shipments of products that did not fall under the embargo.
As the paper indicates, reduced volumes of products prohibited for import were compensated on account of an import increase from countries of the CIS, Africa, South-East Asia, Serbia.
To recap, at the end of August the government extended until 31 December 2020 the validity period of rules on the destruction of agricultural products, primary produce and foodstuffs prohibited for import to Russia within the framework of counter sanctions.
The document, published on the official portal of legislative information, notes that the validity period of the rules was extended for one more year – from 31 December 2019 to 31 December 2020.
Initially the decree on the destruction of sanctioned goods was applied to products from the USA, the EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, from 13 August 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland and Lichtenstein "joined" the list, and from 1 January 2016 – Ukraine.
The decree signed by Putin about the destruction of "sanctioned" products (products falling under the import ban, which Moscow introduced in response to the West's anti-Russian sanctions) illegally imported into the country came into force in 2015.
In turn, the government permitted "sanctioned" foodstuffs to be destroyed by any legal means.
To the extent that the West's sanctions are maintained, Russia also extended its counter measures.
At the same time the said measure does not apply to foodstuffs that citizens import for personal consumption.
The ban does not apply to the import of products for personal use of up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Russian Presidential Council for the Development of Civil Society and Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov earlier described the destruction of foodstuffs as "simply immoral", and this, in his words, has a negative effect on people's development.
In addition, at the beginning of June the Federal Service for the Oversight of Consumer Protection and Welfare proposed banning the destruction of foodstuffs.
After that the presidential council for human rights gave a similar recommendation to the government.
And Russian deputy prime minister Alexei Gordeyev said that destroying foodstuffs is wrong, and that it is necessary to think how to use them for their intended purpose, having evaluated their quality.
A company director was found guilty of tax evasion
A Leninsky district court in the city of Cheboksary, found the director of the Zemlya i Pravo company, Vyacheslav Morozov, guilty of a criminal violation of p. b, pt. 2 of Article 199 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (tax evasion by an organization by deliberately using false information in a tax return, committed on a large scale) and pt. 2 of Article 327 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (forging of an official document providing rights and exemptions from requirements, with a goal of concealing another crime and facilitating its perpetration.
The sentence was announced by the press service of the Investigative Department of the Investigative Committee of Russia for Chuvashia.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vlyacheslav Morozov included incomplete transactions in the company's tax records.
According to the fictitious documents, the company incurred additional expenses and, correspondingly, the amount of taxes paid on added value and on the organization's profits were reduced by 11.2 million rubles.
Vlyacheslav Morozov was sentenced to 3 1/2 years' probation.
First new-format school to open in capital's center by 2023
The new-type school will open in Khamovniki.
According to Moskomstroyinvest head Anastasiya Pyatova, all conditions will be created there for children's self-realization and the development of their talents.
The educational institution will be called Novy Vzglyad.
The Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs' Moscow State Institute of International Relations and the Higher School Economic Development Fund will oversee the project.
Design work on the building of about 10 thousand square meters will start next year.
Construction will be completed at the end of 2022, and selection of the first pupils will start in the following year.
"The project provides for the creation of a widely accessible, noncommercial educational space founded on the traditions of the classical Moscow school and experimental methodologies," said the Moskomstroyinvest press service.
Chile starts building 1 billion euro telescope
This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ESO).
As ESO reports, construction began this week on the dome of the building, where the E-ELT (European Extremely Large Telescope), the most expensive and ambitious terrestrial astronomical project thus far, will be placed.
According to ESO estimates, the total cost will exceed a billion euros.
The bulk of this money will be spent on preparing equipment and building the observatory building.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record-large window, which will have a diameter of about 39 meters.
It will be assembled from 798 1.4-meter hexagonal segments.
This huge mirror and two auxiliary reflecting surfaces with diameters of 4.2 and 3.75 meters will help the E-ELT get the first detailed photographs of planets outside the solar system and stars in other galaxies, and also search for Earth analogs.
Additionally, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the surroundings of Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole in the center of the Milky Way.
Although the construction of the dome has just begun, the mirrors, scientific instruments, and other components of the observatory were already developed by scientists, engineers, and other specialists three years ago—from the time the first plans for building the E-ELT were announced.
The German firm SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc received the contract for producing the main mirror, whose total cost was about 400 million euros.
